future of curatorship? Is there a vision for an ideal model, a curatopia, whether in the form of a utopia or dystopia? Or is there a plurality of approaches, amounting to a curatorial heterotopia? This pioneering volume addresses these questions by considering the current state of curatorship. It reviews the different models and approaches operating in museums, galleries and cultural organisations around the world and discusses emerging concerns, challenges and opportunities. The collection explores the ways in which the mutual, asymmetrical relations underpinning global, scientific entanglements of the past can be transformed into more reciprocal, symmetrical forms of cross-cultural curatorship in the present, arguing that this is the most effective way for curatorial practice to remain meaningful. International in scope, the volume covers three regions: Europe, North America and the Pacific.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aMuseumsxCuratorship. 7aART / Museum Studies.2bisacsh  aAnthropology.  aCurator Curating.  aCurator/curating/curatorship.  aEthnography.  aEurope/Americas/Pacific.  aHistory.  aIndigenous Native Tribal.  aMuseum.  aMuseums.  aResearch.  aTheory and practice.  aanthropology/ethnology.  acollections.  aexhibitions.  afuture.  aindigenous.1 aClifford, James, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDürr, Eveline, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFörster, Larissa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaskell, Ivan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGolding, Viv, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHakiwai, Arapata, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHereniko, Vilsoni, econtribu